                <history>
                    <origin>Both this MS and <ref type="altMs">Montpellier, Ecole de Medicine 452</ref> derive from a now lost exemplar, referred to as <foreign>liber antiquissimus</foreign>. It was discovered in Vercelli in 1442 by Cyriac of Ancona. In both copies the text of Cicero has neither scholia nor illustrations, but the exemplar had scholia derived from Hyginus' Astronomia and the Revised Aratus Latinus (the so called Scholia Sangermanensia). The exemplar was discussed by Kauffmann (who did not know the MSS in the Ambrosiana, Montpellier and Göttweig); Kauffmann's conclusions were summarised and re-confurmed by Reeve.</origin>
